ading the\nentire reference surface."},"151":{"id":"/docs/api/for-agents-66","page_id":"/docs/api/for-agents","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/api/for-agents#five-rules-for-generating-flopscope-code","content":"**1. A global default budget is active automatically — use `BudgetContext` for control.**"},"152":{"id":"/docs/api/for-agents-67","page_id":"/docs/api/for-agents","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/api/for-agents#five-rules-for-generating-flopscope-code","content":"A global default budget auto-activates when flopscope is imported, so quick\nscripts work without any setup. For precise budget control and namespacing,\nuse an explicit `BudgetContext`. Both forms are valid:"},"153":{"id":"/docs/api/for-agents-68","page_id":"/docs/api/for-agents","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/api/for-agents#five-rules-for-generating-flopscope-code","content":"**2. Know what's free and what's counted.**"},"154":{"id":"/docs/api/for-agents-69","page_id":"/docs/api/for-agents","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/api/for-agents#five-rules-for-generating-flopscope-code","content":"Free (0 FLOPs): `zeros`, `ones`, `reshape`, `transpose`, `copy`,\n`random.seed`, `random.get_state`, `random.set_state`, `random.default_rng`."},"155":{"id":"/docs/api/for-agents-70","page_id":"/docs/api/for-agents","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/api/for-agents#five-rules-for-generating-flopscope-code","content":"Custom cost (numel FLOPs): `array`, `linspace`, `arange`, `concatenate`, `where`.\nThese are NOT free — each charges `numel(output)` FLOPs against the budget."},"156":{"id":"/docs/api/for-agents-71","page_id":"/docs/api/for-agents","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/api/for-agents#five-rules-for-generating-flopscope-code","content":"Counted: `einsum`, `dot`, `matmul`, `exp`, `log`, `add`, `multiply`, `sum`,\n`mean`, all `linalg.*`, all `fft.*`, `sort`, `argsort`, `trace`,\n`unique`, set ops (`in1d`, `isin`, etc.), `histogram`, `random.*` sampling."},"157":{"id":"/docs/api/for-agents-72","page_id":"/docs/api/for-agents","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/api/for-agents#five-rules-for-generating-flopscope-code","content":"Blocked: `save`, `load`, `geterr`, `seterr`, and 28 others. These raise\n`AttributeError`."},"158":{"id":"/docs/api/for-agents-73","page_id":"/docs/api/for-agents","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/api/for-agents#five-rules-for-generating-flopscope-code","content":"When in doubt, check `ops.json`, the relevant `/api-data/ops/<slug>.json`, or the API Reference."},"159":{"id":"/docs/api/for-agents-74","page_id":"/docs/api/for-agents","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/api/for-agents#five-rules-for-generating-flopscope-code","content":"**3. Use `flops.accounting.*` to estimate costs before running.**"},"160":{"id":"/docs/api/for-agents-75","page_id":"/docs/api/for-agents","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/api/for-agents#five-rules-for-generating-flopscope-code","content":"These are pure functions — no `BudgetContext` needed."},"161":{"id":"/docs/api/for-agents-76","page_id":"/docs/api/for-agents","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/api/for-agents#five-rules-for-generating-flopscope-code","content":"**4. Use `fnp.einsum` as the primary computation primitive.**"},"162":{"id":"/docs/api/for-agents-77","page_id":"/docs/api/for-agents","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/api/for-agents#five-rules-for-generating-flopscope-code","content":"Most linear algebra can be expressed as einsum. The cost is simply the\nproduct of all index dimensions — each FMA (fused multiply-add) counts\nas 1 operation.\n`'ij,jk->ik'` with shapes `(m, k)` and `(k, n)` costs `m * k * n` FLOPs."},"163":{"id":"/docs/api/for-agents-78","page_id":"/docs/api/for-agents","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/api/for-agents#five-rules-for-generating-flopscope-code","content":"**5. Use `wall_time_limit_s` for time-limited execution.**"},"164":{"id":"/docs/api/for-agents-79","page_id":"/docs/api/for-agents","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/api/for-agents#five-rules-for-generating-flopscope-code","content":"In competition evaluation, submissions run under both a FLOP budget and a\nwall-clock time limit. Test locally with:"},"165":{"id":"/docs/api/for-agents-80","page_id":"/docs/api/for-agents","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/api/for-agents#five-rules-for-generating-flopscope-code","content":"If the time limit is exceeded, `TimeExhaustedError` is raised at the next\noperation boundary. The error includes the operation name, elapsed time, and\nconfigured limit for diagnostics."},"166":{"id":"/docs/api/for-agents-81","page_id":"/docs/api/for-agents","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/api/for-agents#five-rules-for-generating-flopscope-code","content":"**6. Exploit symmetry for cost savings.**"},"167":{"id":"/docs/api/for-agents-82","page_id":"/docs/api/for-agents","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/api/for-agents#five-rules-for-generating-flopscope-code","content":"Use `symmetric_axes` for symmetric outputs:\n`fnp.einsum('ki,kj->ij', X, X, symmetric_axes=[(0, 1)])`"},"168":{"id":"/docs/api/for-agents-83","page_id":"/docs/api/for-agents","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/api/for-agents#five-rules-for-generating-flopscope-code","content":"Wrap known-symmetric matrices with `flops.as_symmetric(data, symmetric_axes=(0, 1))`\nfor automatic savings in downstream ops"},"169":{"id":"/docs/api/for-agents-84","page_id":"/docs/api/for-agents","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/api/for-agents#common-mistakes-agents-make","content":"Mistake"},"170":{"id":"/docs/api/for-agents-85","page_id":"/docs/api/for-agents","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/api/for-agents#common-mistakes-agents-make","content":"What happens"},"171":{"id":"/docs/api/for-agents-86","page_id":"/docs/api/for-agents","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/api/for-agents#common-mistakes-agents-make","content":"Fix"},"172":{"id":"/docs/api/for-agents-87","page_id":"/docs/api/for-agents","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/api/for-agents#common-mistakes-agents-make","content":"Using `np.einsum` instead of `fnp.einsum`"},"173":{"id":"/docs/api/for-agents-88","page_id":"/docs/api/for-agents","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/api/for-agents#common-mistakes-agents-make","content":"FLOPs not counted, budget not checked"},"174":{"id":"/docs/api/for-agents-89","page_id":"/docs/api/for-agents","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/api/for-agents#common-mistakes-agents-make","content":"Always use `fnp.*` for counted NumPy-like operations"},"175":{"id":"/docs/api/for-agents-90","page_id":"/docs/api/for-agents","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/api/for-agents#common-mistakes-agents-make","content":"Skipping `BudgetContext` entirely"},"176":{"id":"/docs/api/for-agents-91","page_id":"/docs/api/for-agents","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/api/for-agents#common-mistakes-agents-make","content":"No error (global default handles it), but budget is harder to track and namespace"},"177":{"id":"/docs/api/for-agents-92","page_id":"/docs/api/for-agents","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/api/for-agents#common-mistakes-agents-make","content":"Use an explicit `BudgetContext` for any work you want to measure or label"},"178":{"id":"/docs/api/for-agents-93","page_id":"/docs/api/for-agents","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/api/for-agents#common-mistakes-agents-make","content":"Assuming `array`, `linspace`, `concatenate`, `where` are free"},"179":{"id":"/docs/api/for-agents-94","page_id":"/docs/api/for-agents","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/api/for-agents#common-mistakes-agents-make","content":"Underestimates budget usage — each charges `numel(output)` FLOPs"},"180":{"id":"/docs/api/for-agents-95","page_id":"/docs/api/for-agents","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/api/for-agents#common-mistakes-agents-make","content":"These are custom-cost ops, not free; check the cheat sheet"},"181":{"id":"/docs/api/for-agents-96","page_id":"/docs/api/for-agents","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/api/for-agents#common-mistakes-agents-make","content":"Assuming `sort` is free"},"182":{"id":"/docs/api/for-agents-97","page_id":"/docs/api/for-agents","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/api/for-agents#common-mistakes-agents-make","content":"Underestimates budget usage"},"183":{"id":"/docs/api/for-agents-98","page_id":"/docs/api/for-agents","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/api/for-agents#common-mistakes-agents-make","content":"`sort` costs `n*ceil(log2(n))` per slice — check the cheat sheet"},"184":{"id":"/docs/api/for-agents-99","page_id":"/docs/api/for-agents","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/api/for-agents#common-mistakes-agents-make","content":"Using `fnp.save()` or `fnp.load()`"},"185":{"id":"/docs/api/for-agents-100","page_id":"/docs/api/for-agents","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/api/for-agents#common-mistakes-agents-make","content":"`AttributeError` — blocked"},"186":{"id":"/docs/api/for-agents-101","page_id":"/docs/api/for-agents","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/api/for-agents#common-mistakes-agents-make","content":"Use `numpy` directly for I/O"},"187":{"id":"/docs/api/for-agents-102","page_id":"/docs/api/for-agents","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/api/for-agents#common-mistakes-agents-make","content":"Nesting two explicit `BudgetContext` blocks"},"188":{"id":"/docs/api/for-agents-103","page_id":"/docs/api/for-agents","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/api/for-agents#common-mistakes-agents-make","content":"`RuntimeError`"},"189":{"id":"/docs/api/for-agents-104","page_id":"/docs/api/for-agents","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/api/for-agents#common-mistakes-agents-make","content":"Use a single explicit context; nesting with the global default is fine"},"190":{"id":"/docs/api/for-agents-105","page_id":"/docs/api/for-agents","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/api/for-agents#common-mistakes-agents-make","content":"Ignoring `wall_time_limit_s` in testing"},"191":{"id":"/docs/api/for-agents-106","page_id":"/docs/api/for-agents","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/api/for-agents#common-mistakes-agents-make","content":"`TimeExhaustedError` in competition"},"192":{"id":"/docs/api/for-agents-107","page_id":"/docs/api/for-agents","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/api/for-agents#common-mistakes-agents-make","content":"Test with a time limit locally to catch slow code early"},"193":{"id":"/docs/api/for-agents-108","page_id":"/docs/api/for-agents","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/api/for-agents#related-pages","content":"API Reference — full operation inventory and cost reference"},"194":{"id":"/docs/api/for-agents-109","page_id":"/docs/api/for-agents","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/api/for-agents#related-pages","content":"Exploit Symmetry — detailed symmetry guide"},"195":{"id":"/docs/api","page_id":"/docs/api","type":"page","content":"API Reference","breadcrumbs":["Documentation","API Reference"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/api"},"196":{"id":"/docs/api-0","page_id":"/docs/api","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/api","content":"Browse Flopscope by namespace, then use the operation cost index when you need a dense cost-oriented lookup."},"197":{"id":"/docs/api/numpy","page_id":"/docs/api/numpy","type":"page","content":"NumPy array routines","breadcrumbs":["Documentation","API Reference"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/api/numpy"},"198":{"id":"/docs/api/numpy-0","page_id":"/docs/api/numpy","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/api/numpy","content":"The counted NumPy-shaped surface for arrays, random sampling, Fourier transforms, and linear algebra."},"199":{"id":"/docs/api/operation-cost-index","page_id":"/docs/api/operation-cost-index","type":"page","content":"Operation Cost Index","breadcrumbs":["Documentation","API Reference"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/api/operation-cost-index"},"200":{"id":"/docs/api/operation-cost-index-0","page_id":"/docs/api/operation-cost-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/api/operation-cost-index","content":"Search and filter counted runtime operations across flopscope.numpy and flopscope.stats."},"201":{"id":"/docs/api/stats","page_id":"/docs/api/stats","type":"page","content":"Statistics","breadcrumbs":["Documentation","API Reference"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/api/stats"},"202":{"id":"/docs/api/stats-0","page_id":"/docs/api/stats","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/api/stats","content":"Distribution objects and their methods for PDFs, CDFs, and inverse CDFs."},"203":{"id":"/docs/development/calibration","page_id":"/docs/development/calibration","type":"page","content":"Calibration & Empirical Weights","breadcrumbs":["Documentation","Development"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/development/calibration"},"204":{"id":"/docs/development/calibration-0","page_id":"/docs/development/calibration","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/development/calibration#what-are-weights","content":"What are weights?"},"205":{"id":"/docs/development/calibration-1","page_id":"/docs/development/calibration","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/development/calibration#quick-start","content":"Quick start"},"206":{"id":"/docs/development/calibration-2","page_id":"/docs/development/calibration","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/development/calibration#using-weights","content":"Using weights"},"207":{"id":"/docs/development/calibration-3","page_id":"/docs/development/calibration","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/development/calibration#default-override-and-disable-behavior","content":"Default, override, and disable behavior"},"208":{"id":"/docs/development/calibration-4","page_id":"/docs/development/calibration","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/development/calibration#programmatic-loading","content":"Programmatic loading"},"209":{"id":"/docs/development/calibration-5","page_id":"/docs/development/calibration","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/development/calibration#how-weights-are-applied","content":"How weights are applied"},"210":{"id":"/docs/development/calibration-6","page_id":"/docs/development/calibration","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/development/calibration#how-measurement-works","content":"How measurement works"},"211":{"id":"/docs/development/calibration-7","page_id":"/docs/development/calibration","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/development/calibration#interpreting-results","content":"Interpreting results"},"212":{"id":"/docs/development/calibration-8","page_id":"/docs/development/calibration","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/development/calibration#related-pages","content":"Related pages"},"213":{"id":"/docs/development/calibration-9","page_id":"/docs/development/calibration","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/development/calibration","content":"*How analytical FLOPs map to real hardware via per-operation weights.*"},"214":{"id":"/docs/development/calibration-10","page_id":"/docs/development/calibration","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/development/calibration","content":"**You will learn:**"},"215":{"id":"/docs/development/calibration-11","page_id":"/docs/development/calibration","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/development/calibration","content":"What per-operation weights are and why they matter"},"216":{"id":"/docs/development/calibration-12","page_id":"/docs/development/calibration","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/development/calibration","content":"How to run calibration and produce a weights config"},"217":{"id":"/docs/development/calibration-13","page_id":"/docs/development/calibration","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/development/calibration","content":"How to load and use weights in your code"},"218":{"id":"/docs/development/calibration-14","page_id":"/docs/development/calibration","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/development/calibration","content":"How the measurement methodology works"},"219":{"id":"/docs/development/calibration-15","page_id":"/docs/development/calibration","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/development/calibration","content":"How to interpret weight values"},"220":{"id":"/docs/development/calibration-16","page_id":"/docs/development/calibration","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/development/calibration#what-are-weights","content":"flopscope's analytical cost formulas treat all operations within a category equally -- `exp`, `log`, `sin`, and `abs` all cost `numel(output)` FLOPs for a pointwise unary operation. In reality, `exp` decomposes into a minimax polynomial approximation requiring approximately 14 floating-point instructions per element, while `abs` is a single bit manipulation."},"221":{"id":"/docs/development/calibration-17","page_id":"/docs/development/calibration","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/development/calibration#what-are-weights","content":"Per-operation **weights** correct for this. Each weight is a multiplicative constant applied on top of the analytical formula:"},"222":{"id":"/docs/development/calibration-18","page_id":"/docs/development/calibration","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/development/calibration#what-are-weights","content":"A weight of 16.0 for `exp` means each analytical FLOP of `exp` is calibrated as approximately 16 times more expensive than one analytical FLOP of `add` under the chosen measurement mode. Known analytical zero-FLOP operations are stored with weight `0.0` in the official artifacts so the generated docs and packaged defaults surface them as truly free. In normal use, flopscope loads packaged official weights automatically on import. Set `FLOPSCOPE_DISABLE_WEIGHTS=1` if you want the pure analytical unit-cost model instead."},"223":{"id":"/docs/development/calibration-19","page_id":"/docs/development/calibration","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/development/calibration#quick-start","content":"Run the benchmark suite to produce a JSON config:"},"224":{"id":"/docs/development/calibration-20","page_id":"/docs/development/calibration","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/development/calibration#quick-start","content":"This benchmarks all 291 operations across 14 categories and writes:"},"225":{"id":"/docs/development/calibration-21","page_id":"/docs/development/calibration","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/development/calibration#quick-start","content":"`weights.json` -- the rich weights config and metadata source for flopscope"},"226":{"id":"/docs/development/calibration-22","page_id":"/docs/development/calibration","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/development/calibration#quick-start","content":"`report.html` -- a human-readable HTML dashboard"},"227":{"id":"/docs/development/calibration-23","page_id":"/docs/development/calibration","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/development/calibration#quick-start","content":"The generated `weights.json` is the source-of-truth artifact: it contains the\nper-operation weights plus metadata used by the generated docs and API data.\nThe packaged runtime file is a slim derivative used only for default loading."},"228":{"id":"/docs/development/calibration-24","page_id":"/docs/development/calibration","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/development/calibration#quick-start","content":"To benchmark only certain categories:"},"229":{"id":"/docs/development/calibration-25","page_id":"/docs/development/calibration","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/development/calibration#quick-start","content":"Available categories: `pointwise`, `reductions`, `linalg`, `linalg_delegates`, `fft`, `sorting`, `random`, `polynomial`, `contractions`, `misc`, `window`, `bitwise`, `complex`."},"230":{"id":"/docs/development/calibration-26","page_id":"/docs/development/calibration","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/development/calibration#default-override-and-disable-behavior","content":"flopscope ships with packaged official weights and loads them automatically on a\nnormal import."},"231":{"id":"/docs/development/calibration-27","page_id":"/docs/development/calibration","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/development/calibration#default-override-and-disable-behavior","content":"Set `FLOPSCOPE_WEIGHTS_FILE` to override those packaged defaults at import time:"},"232":{"id":"/docs/development/calibration-28","page_id":"/docs/development/calibration","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/development/calibration#default-override-and-disable-behavior","content":"Set `FLOPSCOPE_DISABLE_WEIGHTS=1` to disable weighting entirely and use unit\nweights:"},"233":{"id":"/docs/development/calibration-29","page_id":"/docs/development/calibration","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/development/calibration#default-override-and-disable-behavior","content":"The JSON file must have a `\"weights\"` key mapping operation names to floats:"},"234":{"id":"/docs/development/calibration-30","page_id":"/docs/development/calibration","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/development/calibration#default-override-and-disable-behavior","content":"Operations not listed in the override file default to 1.0. A partial config (e.g., pointwise-only) works without error."},"235":{"id":"/docs/development/calibration-31","page_id":"/docs/development/calibration","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/development/calibration#how-weights-are-applied","content":"Weights are applied centrally in `BudgetContext.deduct()`. Every counted operation passes its `op_name` to `deduct()`, which looks up the weight and multiplies it into the cost:"},"236":{"id":"/docs/development/calibration-32","page_id":"/docs/development/calibration","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/development/calibration#how-weights-are-applied","content":"Weights compose with `flop_multiplier` and with symmetry reductions -- symmetry reduces the element count, the weight scales the per-element cost, and both apply independently."},"237":{"id":"/docs/development/calibration-33","page_id":"/docs/development/calibration","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/development/calibration#how-measurement-works","content":"The benchmark suite supports two measurement modes, chosen automatically:"},"238":{"id":"/docs/development/calibration-34","page_id":"/docs/development/calibration","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/development/calibration#how-measurement-works","content":"Mode"},"239":{"id":"/docs/development/calibration-35","page_id":"/docs/development/calibration","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/development/calibration#how-measurement-works","content":"Platform"},"240":{"id":"/docs/development/calibration-36","page_id":"/docs/development/calibration","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/development/calibration#how-measurement-works","content":"What it measures"},"241":{"id":"/docs/development/calibration-37","page_id":"/docs/development/calibration","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/development/calibration#how-measurement-works","content":"**perf**"},"242":{"id":"/docs/development/calibration-38","page_id":"/docs/development/calibration","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/development/calibration#how-measurement-works","content":"Linux (with `perf` installed)"},"243":{"id":"/docs/development/calibration-39","page_id":"/docs/development/calibration","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/development/calibration#how-measurement-works","content":"Instruction-style hardware counters, weighted by SIMD width"},"244":{"id":"/docs/development/calibration-40","page_id":"/docs/development/calibration","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/development/calibration#how-measurement-works","content":"**timing**"},"245":{"id":"/docs/development/calibration-41","page_id":"/docs/development/calibration","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/development/calibration#how-measurement-works","content":"Any (macOS, Linux without `perf`)"},"246":{"id":"/docs/development/calibration-42","page_id":"/docs/development/calibration","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/development/calibration#how-measurement-works","content":"Relative wall-clock cost, normalized against `np.add`"},"247":{"id":"/docs/development/calibration-43","page_id":"/docs/development/calibration","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/development/calibration#how-measurement-works","content":"Every counted operation's weight is computed as:"},"248":{"id":"/docs/development/calibration-44","page_id":"/docs/development/calibration","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/development/calibration#how-measurement-works","content":"Known analytical zero-FLOP operations are not benchmarked; they are emitted\nseparately into the official artifacts with weight `0.0`."},"249":{"id":"/docs/development/calibration-45","page_id":"/docs/development/calibration","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/development/calibration#how-measurement-works","content":"where `alpha_raw(op)` depends on the active measurement mode:"},"250":{"id":"/docs/development/calibration-46","page_id":"/docs/development/calibration","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/development/calibration#how-measurement-works","content":"in **perf** mode, it is the median ratio of counter-observed retired instructions to the analytical FLOP count (FMA = 1 op)"},"251":{"id":"/docs/development/calibration-47","page_id":"/docs/development/calibration","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/development/calibration#how-measurement-works","content":"in **timing** mode, it is the median ratio of wall-clock cost relative to `np.add`, normalized against the same analytical FLOP count"},"252":{"id":"/docs/development/calibration-48","page_id":"/docs/development/calibration","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/development/calibration#how-measurement-works","content":"In other words, perf-mode weights are instruction-oriented calibration factors, while timing-mode weights are relative cost proxies. Both are useful for scaling analytical FLOPs, but timing-mode results should not be read as literal hardware instruction counts."},"253":{"id":"/docs/development/calibration-49","page_id":"/docs/development/calibration","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/development/calibration#how-measurement-works","content":"The ufunc dispatch overhead (measured from `np.abs`, which generates zero FP arithmetic) is subtracted per category to remove NumPy implementation noise from the weight. BLAS-backed operations bypass the ufunc layer and have zero overhead subtracted."},"254":{"id":"/docs/development/calibration-50","page_id":"/docs/development/calibration","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/development/calibration#how-measurement-works","content":"Each measurement uses pre-allocated output arrays to eliminate memory allocation overhead, multiple input distributions for robustness, subprocess isolation to prevent interference, and warmup iterations in timing mode."},"255":{"id":"/docs/development/calibration-51","page_id":"/docs/development/calibration","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/development/calibration#interpreting-results","content":"**weight = 1.0** -- the operation has the same calibrated cost per analytical FLOP as `np.add` under the chosen measurement mode"},"256":{"id":"/docs/development/calibration-52","page_id":"/docs/development/calibration","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/development/calibration#interpreting-results","content":"**weight > 1.0** -- the operation is more expensive per analytical FLOP than `np.add` under the chosen calibration mode (for example, transcendental functions such as `exp`)"},"257":{"id":"/docs/development/calibration-53","page_id":"/docs/development/calibration","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/development/calibration#interpreting-results","content":"**weight \\< 1.0** -- the operation is cheaper per analytical FLOP than `np.add` under the chosen calibration mode. This can happen because of efficient kernels, vectorization, library implementation details, or benchmarking noise; it should not be interpreted using the old “FMA counts as 2 FLOPs” convention, because Flopscope uses FMA = 1 throughout the model"},"258":{"id":"/docs/development/calibration-54","page_id":"/docs/development/calibration","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/development/calibration#interpreting-results","content":"Weights are platform-specific -- different CPUs, BLAS libraries, and libm implementations produce different values. Always measure on the target platform. Symmetry reductions are independent of weights: symmetry reduces the element count while the weight scales the per-element cost."},"259":{"id":"/docs/development/calibration-55","page_id":"/docs/development/calibration","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/development/calibration#interpreting-results","content":"Full per-operation weight data is available in the API Reference and on each standalone operation page under the canonical `/docs/api/...` routes, for example `/docs/api/einsum/`."},"260":{"id":"/docs/development/calibration-56","page_id":"/docs/development/calibration","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/development/calibration#related-pages","content":"FLOP Counting Model -- how weights fit into the cost model"},"261":{"id":"/docs/development/calibration-57","page_id":"/docs/development/calibration","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/development/calibration#related-pages","content":"Budget Planning & Debugging -- query costs before running"},"262":{"id":"/docs/development/contributing","page_id":"/docs/development/contributing","type":"page","content":"Contributor Guide","breadcrumbs":["Documentation","Development"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/development/contributing"},"263":{"id":"/docs/development/contributing-0","page_id":"/docs/development/contributing","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/development/contributing#repository-layout","content":"Repository layout"},"264":{"id":"/docs/development/contributing-1","page_id":"/docs/development/contributing","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/development/contributing#initial-setup","content":"Initial setup"},"265":{"id":"/docs/development/contributing-2","page_id":"/docs/development/contributing","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/development/contributing#which-environment-to-use","content":"Which environment to use"},"266":{"id":"/docs/development/contributing-3","page_id":"/docs/development/contributing","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/do