,"content":"The three ways to draw random samples in flopscope and when to use each"},"832":{"id":"/docs/guides/random-17","page_id":"/docs/guides/random","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/random","content":"How `default_rng()` is the canonical, recommended pattern"},"833":{"id":"/docs/guides/random-18","page_id":"/docs/guides/random","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/random","content":"How counted RNGs behave under pickle/copy/spawn"},"834":{"id":"/docs/guides/random-19","page_id":"/docs/guides/random","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/random","content":"How they integrate with downstream APIs (e.g. future `flopscope.stats.rvs()`)"},"835":{"id":"/docs/guides/random-20","page_id":"/docs/guides/random","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/random","content":"The one foot-gun left over from numpy's legacy API"},"836":{"id":"/docs/guides/random-21","page_id":"/docs/guides/random","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/random#tldr","content":"This is the **canonical pattern**: per-call seed, per-instance state, fully isolated, FLOP-counted."},"837":{"id":"/docs/guides/random-22","page_id":"/docs/guides/random","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/random#three-ways-to-sample","content":"API"},"838":{"id":"/docs/guides/random-23","page_id":"/docs/guides/random","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/random#three-ways-to-sample","content":"Status"},"839":{"id":"/docs/guides/random-24","page_id":"/docs/guides/random","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/random#three-ways-to-sample","content":"Per-instance state?"},"840":{"id":"/docs/guides/random-25","page_id":"/docs/guides/random","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/random#three-ways-to-sample","content":"Use when"},"841":{"id":"/docs/guides/random-26","page_id":"/docs/guides/random","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/random#three-ways-to-sample","content":"`fnp.random.default_rng(seed)`"},"842":{"id":"/docs/guides/random-27","page_id":"/docs/guides/random","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/random#three-ways-to-sample","content":"**canonical** ✅"},"843":{"id":"/docs/guides/random-28","page_id":"/docs/guides/random","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/random#three-ways-to-sample","content":"yes"},"844":{"id":"/docs/guides/random-29","page_id":"/docs/guides/random","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/random#three-ways-to-sample","content":"always (modern code)"},"845":{"id":"/docs/guides/random-30","page_id":"/docs/guides/random","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/random#three-ways-to-sample","content":"`fnp.random.RandomState(seed)`"},"846":{"id":"/docs/guides/random-31","page_id":"/docs/guides/random","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/random#three-ways-to-sample","content":"first-class"},"847":{"id":"/docs/guides/random-32","page_id":"/docs/guides/random","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/random#three-ways-to-sample","content":"yes"},"848":{"id":"/docs/guides/random-33","page_id":"/docs/guides/random","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/random#three-ways-to-sample","content":"porting code from numpy's legacy API"},"849":{"id":"/docs/guides/random-34","page_id":"/docs/guides/random","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/random#three-ways-to-sample","content":"`fnp.random.randn(...)`, `normal(...)`, etc."},"850":{"id":"/docs/guides/random-35","page_id":"/docs/guides/random","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/random#three-ways-to-sample","content":"first-class"},"851":{"id":"/docs/guides/random-36","page_id":"/docs/guides/random","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/random#three-ways-to-sample","content":"shares numpy's global RNG"},"852":{"id":"/docs/guides/random-37","page_id":"/docs/guides/random","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/random#three-ways-to-sample","content":"short scripts, REPL exploration"},"853":{"id":"/docs/guides/random-38","page_id":"/docs/guides/random","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/random#three-ways-to-sample","content":"All three charge FLOPs to the active `BudgetContext`. The difference is *where the random state lives*."},"854":{"id":"/docs/guides/random-39","page_id":"/docs/guides/random","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/random#default_rng--canonical-pattern","content":"The returned object is a `numpy.random.Generator` subclass — `isinstance(rng, np.random.Generator)` holds, so it works anywhere a numpy `Generator` is expected."},"855":{"id":"/docs/guides/random-40","page_id":"/docs/guides/random","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/random#randomstate--legacy-compat","content":"The legacy `numpy.random.RandomState` API is still supported with full FLOP counting:"},"856":{"id":"/docs/guides/random-41","page_id":"/docs/guides/random","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/random#randomstate--legacy-compat","content":"Use this only when you're porting code that already uses `RandomState`. New code should prefer `default_rng()`."},"857":{"id":"/docs/guides/random-42","page_id":"/docs/guides/random","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/random#module-level-samplers","content":"`fnp.random.randn`, `normal`, `uniform`, `choice`, `shuffle`, etc. are kept first-class for short scripts and REPL use:"},"858":{"id":"/docs/guides/random-43","page_id":"/docs/guides/random","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/random#module-level-samplers","content":"These match `numpy.random` semantics exactly, plus FLOP accounting. **They share numpy's global RNG state**, which is fine for one-shot scripts but creates a foot-gun in longer-running programs — see Pitfall: global state below."},"859":{"id":"/docs/guides/random-44","page_id":"/docs/guides/random","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/random#cross-api-parity","content":"Same physical operation charges identical FLOPs regardless of which API you used:"},"860":{"id":"/docs/guides/random-45","page_id":"/docs/guides/random","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/random#cross-api-parity","content":"`default_rng().normal(...)` inherits the calibrated weight of the module-level `random.normal` it shadows. No per-method calibration is needed for new method-level entries — runtime aliasing handles it."},"861":{"id":"/docs/guides/random-46","page_id":"/docs/guides/random","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/random#pickle-and-copy","content":"Counted RNGs round-trip cleanly through `pickle` and `copy`:"},"862":{"id":"/docs/guides/random-47","page_id":"/docs/guides/random","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/random#spawn-for-parallel-work","content":"`Generator.spawn(n)` returns `n` independent counted children that share no state with the parent:"},"863":{"id":"/docs/guides/random-48","page_id":"/docs/guides/random","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/random#spawn-for-parallel-work","content":"Each child has its own `bit_generator`, so children running in parallel produce independent streams — no contention, no shared state."},"864":{"id":"/docs/guides/random-49","page_id":"/docs/guides/random","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/random#constructing-from-a-specific-bitgenerator","content":"The `Generator(BitGenerator(seed))` idiom from numpy works identically:"},"865":{"id":"/docs/guides/random-50","page_id":"/docs/guides/random","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/random#constructing-from-a-specific-bitgenerator","content":"The bit-generator classes (`BitGenerator`, `MT19937`, `PCG64`, `PCG64DXSM`, `Philox`, `SFC64`) pass through to numpy unchanged — they don't do math, so there's nothing to count at the bit-generator level. FLOPs are charged at the sampler-method level on the resulting `Generator`."},"866":{"id":"/docs/guides/random-51","page_id":"/docs/guides/random","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/random#pitfall-global-state","content":"The one path that *doesn't* give per-instance isolation is the module-level samplers, because they share numpy's global RNG. Across two sequential `BudgetContext`s:"},"867":{"id":"/docs/guides/random-52","page_id":"/docs/guides/random","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/random#pitfall-global-state","content":"If you need each context to be independently reproducible, either re-seed at the top of each context, or use `default_rng()`:"},"868":{"id":"/docs/guides/random-53","page_id":"/docs/guides/random","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/random#pitfall-global-state","content":"Note that **`BudgetContext`s cannot be nested** at all (the runtime raises `RuntimeError(\"Cannot nest BudgetContexts\")`), so the global-state issue only affects *sequential* contexts, never overlapping ones."},"869":{"id":"/docs/guides/random-54","page_id":"/docs/guides/random","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/random#forward-compatibility-integration-with-other-apis","content":"Anything that accepts a numpy `Generator` accepts a counted `Generator`. For example, when `flopscope.stats` grows an `rvs()` method (random variate sampling), it will accept a counted RNG and inherit FLOP counting for free:"},"870":{"id":"/docs/guides/random-55","page_id":"/docs/guides/random","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/random#forward-compatibility-integration-with-other-apis","content":"The pattern works because `rng.uniform(...)` and `fnp.stats.norm.ppf(...)` are both already FLOP-counted. Inverse-CDF sampling threads naturally through the existing wrappers."},"871":{"id":"/docs/guides/random-56","page_id":"/docs/guides/random","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/random#whats-deliberately-not-supported","content":"Pattern"},"872":{"id":"/docs/guides/random-57","page_id":"/docs/guides/random","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/random#whats-deliberately-not-supported","content":"Status"},"873":{"id":"/docs/guides/random-58","page_id":"/docs/guides/random","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/random#whats-deliberately-not-supported","content":"Why"},"874":{"id":"/docs/guides/random-59","page_id":"/docs/guides/random","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/random#whats-deliberately-not-supported","content":"Nested `BudgetContext`s"},"875":{"id":"/docs/guides/random-60","page_id":"/docs/guides/random","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/random#whats-deliberately-not-supported","content":"runtime error"},"876":{"id":"/docs/guides/random-61","page_id":"/docs/guides/random","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/random#whats-deliberately-not-supported","content":"Out of scope; flopscope models a single budget per program region."},"877":{"id":"/docs/guides/random-62","page_id":"/docs/guides/random","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/random#whats-deliberately-not-supported","content":"Methods not in the registry"},"878":{"id":"/docs/guides/random-63","page_id":"/docs/guides/random","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/random#whats-deliberately-not-supported","content":"`UnsupportedFunctionError`"},"879":{"id":"/docs/guides/random-64","page_id":"/docs/guides/random","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/random#whats-deliberately-not-supported","content":"Closes the silent-bypass hole from issue #18. New numpy methods are added to the registry on each version bump (CI: `scripts/numpy_audit.py --ci`)."},"880":{"id":"/docs/guides/random-65","page_id":"/docs/guides/random","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/random#whats-deliberately-not-supported","content":"`numpy.random.<X>` directly"},"881":{"id":"/docs/guides/random-66","page_id":"/docs/guides/random","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/random#whats-deliberately-not-supported","content":"not counted"},"882":{"id":"/docs/guides/random-67","page_id":"/docs/guides/random","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/random#whats-deliberately-not-supported","content":"Use `fnp.random.<X>` for counting. `numpy.random.X` continues to work but bypasses flopscope."},"883":{"id":"/docs/guides/random-68","page_id":"/docs/guides/random","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/random#related","content":"`fnp.random.default_rng` — canonical entry point (op page)"},"884":{"id":"/docs/guides/random-69","page_id":"/docs/guides/random","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/random#related","content":"Migrate from NumPy — broader migration guide"},"885":{"id":"/docs/guides/random-70","page_id":"/docs/guides/random","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/random#related","content":"Issue #18 — design rationale and history"},"886":{"id":"/docs/guides/random-71","page_id":"/docs/guides/random","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/random#related","content":"(`fnp.random.RandomState` is a class constructor, not a registered op — its\nsampler methods have individual op pages under `/docs/api/numpy/random/`.)"},"887":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","type":"page","content":"Symmetry Savings","breadcrumbs":["Documentation","Guides"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/symmetry"},"888":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-0","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#why-symmetry-matters","content":"Why symmetry matters"},"889":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-1","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#quick-start","content":"Quick start"},"890":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-2","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#how-to-declare-symmetry","content":"How to declare symmetry"},"891":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-3","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#full-symmetry-with-symmetrygroupsymmetric","content":"Full symmetry with `SymmetryGroup.symmetric`"},"892":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-4","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#multiple-independent-full-symmetric-groups","content":"Multiple independent full symmetric groups"},"893":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-5","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#explicit-full-symmetric-groups-with-symmetrygroupsymmetric","content":"Explicit full symmetric groups with `SymmetryGroup.symmetric`"},"894":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-6","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#cyclic-symmetry-with-symmetrygroupcyclic","content":"Cyclic symmetry with `SymmetryGroup.cyclic`"},"895":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-7","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#dihedral-symmetry-with-symmetrygroupdihedral","content":"Dihedral symmetry with `SymmetryGroup.dihedral`"},"896":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-8","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#arbitrary-subgroups-from-custom-generators","content":"Arbitrary subgroups from custom generators"},"897":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-9","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#multiple-explicit-groups-on-one-tensor","content":"Multiple explicit groups on one tensor"},"898":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-10","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#generating-example-data-with-the-reynolds-operator","content":"Generating example data with the Reynolds operator"},"899":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-11","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#symmetry-propagation-at-a-glance","content":"Symmetry propagation at a glance"},"900":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-12","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#slicing-rules","content":"Slicing rules"},"901":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-13","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#reduction-rules","content":"Reduction rules"},"902":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-14","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#binary-pointwise-ops-and-broadcasting","content":"Binary pointwise ops and broadcasting"},"903":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-15","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#warnings-conservative-behavior-and-re-tagging","content":"Warnings, conservative behavior, and re-tagging"},"904":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-16","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#edge-cases-when-symmetrictensors-meet-numpy-protocols","content":"Edge cases when SymmetricTensors meet NumPy protocols"},"905":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-17","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#in-place-dunders-refuse-symmetry-corrupting-writes","content":"In-place dunders refuse symmetry-corrupting writes"},"906":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-18","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#in-place-sort--partition-refuse-on-symmetrictensor","content":"In-place sort / partition refuse on SymmetricTensor"},"907":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-19","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#ufuncat-refuses-on-symmetrictensor","content":"`ufunc.at` refuses on SymmetricTensor"},"908":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-20","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#ufuncouter-produces-direct-product-symmetry","content":"`ufunc.outer` produces direct-product symmetry"},"909":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-21","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#tensordot-keeps-surviving-direct-product-symmetry","content":"`tensordot` keeps surviving direct-product symmetry"},"910":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-22","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#multi-output-ufuncs-preserve-symmetry-on-every-output","content":"Multi-output ufuncs preserve symmetry on every output"},"911":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-23","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#cost-model-is-a-placeholder-above-degree-12","content":"Cost model is a placeholder above degree 12"},"912":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-24","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#under-the-hood","content":"Under the hood"},"913":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-25","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#going-deeper","content":"Going deeper"},"914":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-26","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry","content":"*Reduce FLOP costs when your tensors have symmetry.*"},"915":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-27","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry","content":"**You will learn:**"},"916":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-28","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry","content":"How to declare full and non-full tensor symmetries with `flops.as_symmetric()`"},"917":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-29","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry","content":"How to generate example tensors for arbitrary permutation groups"},"918":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-30","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry","content":"When to use `fnp.random.symmetric()` (sample + project) versus `flops.symmetrize()`\n(project existing data)"},"919":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-31","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry","content":"How slicing, reductions, and binary pointwise ops preserve, weaken, or drop symmetry metadata"},"920":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-32","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry","content":"When to re-tag results with `flops.as_symmetric()` after conservative propagation"},"921":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-33","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#why-symmetry-matters","content":"Many tensors contain repeated structure. A symmetric matrix has only\n`n * (n + 1) / 2` unique elements instead of `n^2`, and higher-order tensors\nwith permutation symmetry can shrink the effective element count even more.\nWhen Flopscope knows a tensor's symmetry, it charges FLOPs based on unique elements\ninstead of dense ones."},"922":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-34","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#why-symmetry-matters","content":"Operation"},"923":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-35","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#why-symmetry-matters","content":"Dense cost"},"924":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-36","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#why-symmetry-matters","content":"Symmetry-aware cost"},"925":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-37","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#why-symmetry-matters","content":"Why it drops"},"926":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-38","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#why-symmetry-matters","content":"`fnp.exp(s2_matrix)`"},"927":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-39","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#why-symmetry-matters","content":"`n^2`"},"928":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-40","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#why-symmetry-matters","content":"`n * (n + 1) / 2`"},"929":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-41","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#why-symmetry-matters","content":"only unique matrix entries matter"},"930":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-42","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#why-symmetry-matters","content":"`fnp.einsum('ki,kj->ij', x, x, symmetry=flops.SymmetryGroup.symmetric(axes=(0, 1)))`"},"931":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-43","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#why-symmetry-matters","content":"`m * n^2`"},"932":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-44","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#why-symmetry-matters","content":"`m * n * (n + 1) / 2`"},"933":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-45","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#why-symmetry-matters","content":"the repeated `x` operand lets flopscope detect symmetric output and reduce the cost"},"934":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-46","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#why-symmetry-matters","content":"`fnp.einsum('i,j,k->ijk', v, v, v)`"},"935":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-47","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#why-symmetry-matters","content":"`n^3`"},"936":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-48","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#why-symmetry-matters","content":"symmetry-reduced"},"937":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-49","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#why-symmetry-matters","content":"repeated operands induce output symmetry"},"938":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-50","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#why-symmetry-matters","content":"By contrast, declaring `symmetry=` on an `einsum` output tags the result for downstream\noperations; it does not reduce that `einsum`'s own cost by itself."},"939":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-51","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#quick-start","content":"`flops.as_symmetric()` validates the data first. After that, Flopscope propagates\nsymmetry metadata algebraically through many operations. Unary pointwise ops preserve symmetry-aware costs and keep the same exact group, including non-full groups such as `C_k` or `D_k`. Slicing, reductions, and binary pointwise ops can weaken it or remove it entirely."},"940":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-52","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#full-symmetry-with-symmetrygroupsymmetric","content":"Use `SymmetryGroup.symmetric` when the tensor is invariant under every permutation of a\nset of axes."},"941":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-53","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#full-symmetry-with-symmetrygroupsymmetric","content":"This is the most common declaration: full `S_2` symmetry on matrix axes\n`(0, 1)`."},"942":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-54","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#multiple-independent-full-symmetric-groups","content":"This declares one full symmetric group on axes `(0, 1)` and another on\n`(2, 3)`."},"943":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-55","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#explicit-full-symmetric-groups-with-symmetrygroupsymmetric","content":"This explicit group is useful once you want to inspect or combine symmetry directly."},"944":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-56","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#cyclic-symmetry-with-symmetrygroupcyclic","content":"`C_3` means rotations are allowed, but reflections are not. This is weaker\nthan `S_3`, so it usually gives fewer savings."},"945":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-57","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#dihedral-symmetry-with-symmetrygroupdihedral","content":"`D_4` includes both rotations and reflections of a four-position structure."},"946":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-58","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#arbitrary-subgroups-from-custom-generators","content":"Use this form when the built-in constructors do not describe your symmetry."},"947":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-59","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#multiple-explicit-groups-on-one-tensor","content":"This uses a direct product of two exact symmetry factors, one on `(0, 1)` and one on `(2, 3)`."},"948":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-60","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#generating-example-data-with-the-reynolds-operator","content":"When you want example tensors for arbitrary groups, prefer `fnp.random.symmetric`.\nIt is a handy helper that samples from a distribution and applies the Reynolds\noperator.\nUse `flops.symmetrize` when you already have concrete data to symmetrize, and\n`flops.as_symmetric` when you already have concrete data to validate and tag."},"949":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-61","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#generating-example-data-with-the-reynolds-operator","content":"`R_G(T) = (1 / |G|) * sum_{g in G} g · T`"},"950":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-62","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#generating-example-data-with-the-reynolds-operator","content":"This helper is ideal for docs, tests, and experiments:"},"951":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-63","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#generating-example-data-with-the-reynolds-operator","content":"it works for `S_k`, `C_k`, `D_k`, and custom generator sets"},"952":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-64","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#generating-example-data-with-the-reynolds-operator","content":"prefer `fnp.random.symmetric()` for synthetic data generation"},"953":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-65","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#generating-example-data-with-the-reynolds-operator","content":"`fnp.random.symmetric` internally samples data and calls `flops.symmetrize` so the\nprojection and validation behavior is identical."},"954":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-66","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#generating-example-data-with-the-reynolds-operator","content":"approximate costs (meaningful estimate):"},"955":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-67","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#generating-example-data-with-the-reynolds-operator","content":"`fnp.random.symmetric`: `C_dist(n) + |G| * n + n` + validation"},"956":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-68","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#generating-example-data-with-the-reynolds-operator","content":"`flops.symmetrize`: `|G| * n + n` + validation\\\nwith `n` total elements and `|G|` group order."},"957":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-69","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#generating-example-data-with-the-reynolds-operator","content":"in exact arithmetic it projects onto the invariant subspace, and in practice\n`flops.as_symmetric()` validates the result with its usual validation tolerances"},"958":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-70","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#generating-example-data-with-the-reynolds-operator","content":"it keeps examples consistent across symmetry classes"},"959":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-71","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#generating-example-data-with-the-reynolds-operator","content":"The propagation examples below assume `import flopscope as flops` plus `import flopscope.numpy as fnp`; generated tensors\nabove use `fnp.random.symmetric(...)` and the explicit transform helper is\n`flops.symmetrize(...)`."},"960":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-72","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#symmetry-propagation-at-a-glance","content":"Symmetry propagation is conservative. Flopscope keeps symmetry metadata only when\nthe operation's structure guarantees that the output still respects the\nsurviving group."},"961":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-73","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#symmetry-propagation-at-a-glance","content":"Operation"},"962":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-74","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#symmetry-propagation-at-a-glance","content":"Result type"},"963":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-75","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#symmetry-propagation-at-a-glance","content":"Rule"},"964":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-76","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#symmetry-propagation-at-a-glance","content":"`fnp.exp(s3_tensor)`"},"965":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-77","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#symmetry-propagation-at-a-glance","content":"`SymmetricTensor`"},"966":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-78","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#symmetry-propagation-at-a-glance","content":"unary pointwise ops preserve the exact declared group"},"967":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-79","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#symmetry-propagation-at-a-glance","content":"`fnp.add(s3_tensor, c3_tensor)`"},"968":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-80","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#symmetry-propagation-at-a-glance","content":"`SymmetricTensor` or `FlopscopeArray`"},"969":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-81","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#symmetry-propagation-at-a-glance","content":"binary pointwise ops keep the intersection of both operands' groups"},"970":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-82","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#symmetry-propagation-at-a-glance","content":"`s2_matrix * 3`"},"971":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-83","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#symmetry-propagation-at-a-glance","content":"`SymmetricTensor`"},"972":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-84","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#symmetry-propagation-at-a-glance","content":"scalar binary ops preserve the tensor's groups"},"973":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-85","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#symmetry-propagation-at-a-glance","content":"`s2_matrix[0]`"},"974":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-86","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#symmetry-propagation-at-a-glance","content":"`FlopscopeArray`"},"975":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-87","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#symmetry-propagation-at-a-glance","content":"integer indexing removes one axis; no nontrivial group survives"},"976":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-88","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#symmetry-propagation-at-a-glance","content":"`s2_matrix[:3, :3]`"},"977":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-89","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#symmetry-propagation-at-a-glance","content":"`SymmetricTensor`"},"978":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-90","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#symmetry-propagation-at-a-glance","content":"equal-size slices can preserve symmetry"},"979":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-91","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#symmetry-propagation-at-a-glance","content":"`s2_matrix[:3, :2]`"},"980":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-92","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#symmetry-propagation-at-a-glance","content":"`FlopscopeArray`"},"981":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-93","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#symmetry-propagation-at-a-glance","content":"unequal-size slices break symmetry between those axes"},"982":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-94","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#symmetry-propagation-at-a-glance","content":"`s2_matrix[fnp.array([0, 1])]`"},"983":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-95","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#symmetry-propagation-at-a-glance","content":"`FlopscopeArray`"},"984":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-96","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#symmetry-propagation-at-a-glance","content":"advanced indexing drops symmetry conservatively"},"985":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-97","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#symmetry-propagation-at-a-glance","content":"`fnp.sum(s3_tensor, axis=0)`"},"986":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-98","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#symmetry-propagation-at-a-glance","content":"`SymmetricTensor`"},"987":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-99","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#symmetry-propagation-at-a-glance","content":"reductions keep the surviving setwise stabilizer subgroup"},"988":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-100","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#symmetry-propagation-at-a-glance","content":"`fnp.sum(d4_tensor, axis=(1, 3))`"},"989":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-101","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#symmetry-propagation-at-a-glance","content":"`SymmetricTensor`"},"990":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-102","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#symmetry-propagation-at-a-glance","content":"reductions can keep a proper subgroup like `C_2`"},"991":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-103","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#symmetry-propagation-at-a-glance","content":"`s2_matrix @ s2_matrix`"},"992":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-104","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#symmetry-propagation-at-a-glance","content":"`FlopscopeArray`"},"993":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-105","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#symmetry-propagation-at-a-glance","content":"matrix products are not assumed symmetric in general"},"994":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-106","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#symmetry-propagation-at-a-glance","content":"`fnp.exp(c3_tensor)` keeps the original `C_3` subgroup exactly; the same applies\nto `D_k` and custom exact groups."},"995":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-107","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#slicing-rules","content":"Slicing uses the **pointwise stabilizer** of the removed axes. Informally:\nevery removed axis must stay fixed under any surviving group element."},"996":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-108","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#slicing-rules","content":"What happens here:"},"997":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-109","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#slicing-rules","content":"`same_size_slice` stays symmetric because both surviving axes still have the\nsame size"},"998":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-110","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#slicing-rules","content":"`different_size_slice` loses symmetry because the two axes no longer match"},"999":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-111","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#slicing-rules","content":"`expanded_s2_matrix` keeps the same `S_2` action, but the axes are renumbered\nfrom `(0, 1)` to `(1, 2)`"},"1000":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-112","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#slicing-rules","content":"`advanced_index_slice` returns a dense `FlopscopeArray`; flopscope does not attempt to\npropagate symmetry through array/list indexing"},"1001":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-113","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#slicing-rules","content":"`Ellipsis` behaves like NumPy's normal expansion rules. It can change which\naxes remain, but it does not change the propagation rule itself."},"1002":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-114","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#slicing-rules","content":"The difference between full and non-full groups matters immediately:"},"1003":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-115","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#slicing-rules","content":"`s3_slice` keeps an `S_2` subgroup on the surviving axes"},"1004":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-116","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#slicing-rules","content":"`c3_slice` loses all nontrivial symmetry, because `C_3` has no non-identity\nelement that fixes one point"},"1005":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-117","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#reduction-rules","content":"Reductions use the **setwise stabilizer** of the reduced axes. Informally:\nreduced axes are allowed to permute among themselves, because summation treats\nall positions along the reduced set equivalently."},"1006":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-118","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#reduction-rules","content":"What happens here:"},"1007":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-119","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#reduction-rules","content":"`s3_reduced` keeps an `S_2` subgroup on the remaining axes"},"1008":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-120","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#reduction-rules","content":"`c3_reduced` loses all nontrivial symmetry"},"1009":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-121","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#reduction-rules","content":"`c4_reduced` keeps a `C_2` subgroup"},"1010":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-122","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#reduction-rules","content":"`c4_keepdims` keeps the same surviving subgroup, but the output axes stay in\ntheir original tensor positions because `keepdims=True`"},"1011":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-123","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#reduction-rules","content":"Reducing an axis that is not in a symmetry group leaves that group alone, apart\nfrom any axis renumbering caused by the removed dimension."},"1012":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-124","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#binary-pointwise-ops-and-broadcasting","content":"Binary pointwise ops keep only the symmetry present in **both** operands. For\ngeneral groups, that means element-set intersection on matching output axes,\nnot just matching tuples of axis numbers."},"1013":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-125","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#binary-pointwise-ops-and-broadcasting","content":"`intersection_tensor` keeps `C_3`, because `C_3` is the common subgroup of\n`S_3` and `C_3`."},"1014":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-126","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#binary-pointwise-ops-and-broadcasting","content":"Multiple groups are handled independently:"},"1015":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-127","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#binary-pointwise-ops-and-broadcasting","content":"`shared_group_tensor` keeps only the swap on `(0, 1)`. In the exact-group\nrepresentation that surviving action is still embedded in the full output rank,\nso the group's support tuple spans `(0, 1, 2, 3)` even though it acts\nnontrivially only on `(0, 1)`."},"1016":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-128","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#binary-pointwise-ops-and-broadcasting","content":"Broadcasting matters too:"},"1017":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-129","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#binary-pointwise-ops-and-broadcasting","content":"Before group intersection, any axis stretched from size `1` to a larger output\nsize is removed from the carried candidate group. So singleton broadcasting by\nitself does not preserve symmetry. In this example, though, `plain_tensor`\nalready carries the same analytically provable `S_2` symmetry on `(0, 1)`, so\n`broadcast_sum` keeps that shared block."},"1018":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-130","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#warnings-conservative-behavior-and-re-tagging","content":"Flopscope propagates symmetry metadata conservatively. When the operation does not\nguarantee that the declared symmetry survives, the result falls back to a dense\n`FlopscopeArray` with no `.symmetry` metadata."},"1019":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-131","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#warnings-conservative-behavior-and-re-tagging","content":"`row_slice` is a plain dense `FlopscopeArray`, not a `SymmetricTensor`. That is expected."},"1020":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-132","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#warnings-conservative-behavior-and-re-tagging","content":"`SymmetryLossWarning` tells you that metadata was dropped or weakened during an\noperation. If you know more about the result than the conservative propagation\nrule does, you can re-tag it with `flops.as_symmetric()`."},"1021":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-133","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#warnings-conservative-behavior-and-re-tagging","content":"One important caveat: the current implementation does **not** report every\npossible partial weakening via `SymmetryLossWarning`. Treat the warning system\nas helpful guidance, not as a complete audit of every same-axis subgroup\nchange."},"1022":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-134","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#edge-cases-when-symmetrictensors-meet-numpy-protocols","content":"Once your tensors flow through arbitrary user code (or third-party libraries), they\ninevitably hit NumPy's `__array_ufunc__` and `__array_function__` machinery —\n`np.add(A, B)`, `np.divmod(A, B)`, `np.add.outer(A, B)`, `np.add.at(A, idx, vals)`,\n`A @= B`, `np.tensordot(A, B, axes=...)`, and so on. Flopscope's\nprotocol implementations are conservative: when an operation would silently\ncorrupt your declared symmetry, flopscope **refuses or strips** rather than letting\nit through. This section is a tour of those edge cases."},"1023":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-135","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#in-place-dunders-refuse-symmetry-corrupting-writes","content":"The right-hand-side has no symmetry, so `A_sym + B_plain` returns a plain\n`FlopscopeArray`. Writing that result back into `A_sym`'s buffer would leave the\nmetadata claiming symmetry while the data is asymmetric. Flopscope refuses with\n`ValueError: in-place add on a SymmetricTensor would weaken or destroy the\ndeclared symmetry`."},"1024":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-136","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#in-place-dunders-refuse-symmetry-corrupting-writes","content":"If you know the asymmetric write is intentional, downgrade first:"},"1025":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-137","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#in-place-dunders-refuse-symmetry-corrupting-writes","content":"The same guard applies to `__isub__`, `__imul__`, `__itruediv__`,\n`__ifloordiv__`, `__imod__`, `__ipow__`, `__iand__`, `__ior__`, `__ixor__`,\n`__ilshift__`, `__irshift__`, and `__imatmul__` (which additionally falls back\nto CPython's rebind-the-name semantics when the matmul output shape differs\nfrom `self.shape`)."},"1026":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-138","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#in-place-sort--partition-refuse-on-symmetrictensor","content":"A reorder along any axis breaks the permutation invariance. Use the out-of-place\nforms instead:"},"1027":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-139","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#ufuncat-refuses-on-symmetrictensor","content":"`np.add.at(a, indices, values)` does an unbuffered fancy-index write — every\nrepeat of an index applies again (unlike `a[indices] += values` which dedupes).\nOn a `SymmetricTensor` this almost certainly breaks symmetry, so flopscope\nrefuses:"},"1028":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-140","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#ufuncat-refuses-on-symmetrictensor","content":"Downgrade with `A_sym.view(fnp.ndarray)` first if you really need the unbuffered\nupdate."},"1029":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-141","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#ufuncouter-produces-direct-product-symmetry","content":"When both operands are symmetric, the output of `np.<ufunc>.outer(A, B)`\ninherits the **direct product** of the input symmetries — `A`'s symmetry on\nits own axes, `B`'s symmetry on the lifted slots `A.ndim..A.ndim+B.ndim-1`:"},"1030":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-142","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#tensordot-keeps-surviving-direct-product-symmetry","content":"The contracted axes drop out of each operand's symmetry; what's left of each\noperand's symmetry on the surviving (uncontracted) axes is direct-producted:"},"1031":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-143","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#tensordot-keeps-surviving-direct-product-symmetry","content":"If the contracted axis is part of the symmetry group, that group is destroyed\non the corresponding side."},"1032":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-144","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#multi-output-ufuncs-preserve-symmetry-on-every-output","content":"`np.divmod(A, B)`, `np.frexp(A)`, `np.modf(A)` are elementwise — both outputs\ninherit the same symmetry as their inputs:"},"1033":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-145","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#multi-output-ufuncs-preserve-symmetry-on-every-output","content":"`out=(o1, o2)` works (per-slot identity is preserved), and `out=(o1, None)`\nlets numpy allocate just the second slot."},"1034":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-146","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#cost-model-is-a-placeholder-above-degree-12","content":"Flopscope charges `dense_cost × unique_output_elements / dense_output_elements` for\n`ufunc.outer` and `tensordot` as a coarse proxy for the savings a\nsymmetry-aware implementation could realise. The underlying NumPy call still\ndoes dense work; only the budget reflects the savings."},"1035":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-147","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#cost-model-is-a-placeholder-above-degree-12","content":"For a `SymmetryGroup` with degree above **12**, flopscope skips this adjustment and\ncharges the full dense cost — `Burnside` enumeration on `S_n` for `n > 12`\nbecomes infeasible (`13! ≈ 6.2 × 10⁹`). The skip is announced via\n`CostFallbackWarning`:"},"1036":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-148","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#cost-model-is-a-placeholder-above-degree-12","content":"This is rare in practice — common user tensors have degree ≤ 8 — but high-rank\nauto-inferred symmetries on degenerate shapes (`(1,)*N` for large `N`) trip\nthe cap. The warning fires once per `(op_name, degree)` pair per process to\navoid log flooding. Suppress with `flops.configure(symmetry_warnings=False)`,\nwhich shares the flag with `SymmetryLossWarning`."},"1037":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-149","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#cost-model-is-a-placeholder-above-degree-12","content":"A proper algorithmic-cost model is a follow-up."},"1038":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-150","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#under-the-hood","content":"The propagation rules are easier to predict if you keep three ideas in mind:"},"1039":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-151","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#under-the-hood","content":"**Unary pointwise ops** preserve symmetry-aware costs, but for\nfull and non-full groups alike they keep the same exact group"},"1040":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-152","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#under-the-hood","content":"**Slicing** uses the pointwise stabilizer of the removed axes"},"1041":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-153","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#under-the-hood","content":"**Reductions** use the setwise stabilizer of the reduced axes"},"1042":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-154","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#under-the-hood","content":"**Binary pointwise ops** use intersection of both operands' groups after\nbroadcast alignment"},"1043":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-155","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#under-the-hood","content":"After computing the surviving subgroup, flopscope restricts it to the axes still\npresent in the output and remaps those axes to the output tensor's numbering."},"1044":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-156","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#under-the-hood","content":"That is why:"},"1045":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-157","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#under-the-hood","content":"slicing one axis of `S_3` leaves `S_2`"},"1046":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-158","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#under-the-hood","content":"slicing one axis of `C_3` leaves nothing nontrivial"},"1047":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-159","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#under-the-hood","content":"reducing `{1, 3}` of `C_4` can still leave `C_2`"},"1048":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-160","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#going-deeper","content":"Einsum Patterns — how declared and induced symmetry interact with `fnp.einsum`"},"1049":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-161","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#going-deeper","content":"Symmetry Detection Deep Dive — the full detection algorithm for `einsum`"},"1050":{"id":"/docs/guides/symmetry-162","page_id":"/docs/guides/symmetry","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/symmetry#going-deeper","content":"Symmetry Explorer — experiment with symmetry interactively"},"1051":{"id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server","page_id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server","type":"page","content":"Client-Server Model","breadcrumbs":["Documentation","Infrastructure"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server"},"1052":{"id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server-0","page_id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server#why-client-server","content":"Why client-server?"},"1053":{"id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server-1","page_id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server#how-it-works","content":"How it works"},"1054":{"id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server-2","page_id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server#communication-protocol","content":"Communication protocol"},"1055":{"id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server-3","page_id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server#api-compatibility","content":"API compatibility"},"1056":{"id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server-4","page_id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server#when-to-use-which","content":"When to use which"},"1057":{"id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server-5","page_id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server#three-packages-in-this-repo","content":"Three packages in this repo"},"1058":{"id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server-6","page_id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server#related-pages","content":"Related pages"},"1059":{"id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server-7","page_id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server","content":"This page covers the client-server architecture used for **competition evaluation**, where participant code runs in an isolated container. For how Flopscope wraps NumPy internally, see How Flopscope Works."},"1060":{"id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server-8","page_id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server","content":"*Use this page to understand how Flopscope's client-server architecture works and why it exists.*"},"1061":{"id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server-9","page_id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server","content":"**You will learn:**"},"1062":{"id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server-10","page_id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server","content":"Why Flopscope uses a client-server model for competition evaluation"},"1063":{"id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server-11","page_id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server","content":"How arrays, operations, and budgets flow between client and server"},"1064":{"id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server-12","page_id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server","content":"How to choose between the local library and client-server packages"},"1065":{"id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server-13","page_id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server#why-client-server","content":"In competition evaluation, participant code runs in an **isolated container** that cannot import NumPy directly. This prevents participants from bypassing FLOP counting by calling NumPy functions outside flopscope."},"1066":{"id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server-14","page_id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server#why-client-server","content":"The client-server model enforces this isolation:"},"1067":{"id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server-15","page_id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server#how-it-works","content":"**Server** runs the real flopscope library backed by NumPy. It stores all arrays, enforces budgets, and counts FLOPs."},"1068":{"id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server-16","page_id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server#how-it-works","content":"**Client** exposes the same public imports (`import flopscope as flops` plus `import flopscope.numpy as fnp`) and proxies every operation to the server over ZMQ (msgpack-encoded messages)."},"1069":{"id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server-17","page_id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server#how-it-works","content":"**Arrays stay on the server.** The client holds lightweight `RemoteArray` handles that reference server-side data. When you call `fnp.einsum(...)`, the client sends the operation and handle IDs to the server, which executes it and returns a new handle."},"1070":{"id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server-18","page_id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server#how-it-works","content":"**Budget enforcement happens server-side.** The client cannot manipulate FLOP counts."},"1071":{"id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server-19","page_id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server#communication-protocol","content":"**Transport:** ZMQ (REQ/REP pattern)"},"1072":{"id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server-20","page_id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server#communication-protocol","content":"**Serialization:** msgpack with binary-safe array payloads"},"1073":{"id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server-21","page_id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server#communication-protocol","content":"**Default endpoint:** `ipc:///tmp/flopscope.sock` (configurable via `FLOPSCOPE_SERVER_URL`)"},"1074":{"id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server-22","page_id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server#communication-protocol","content":"**Timeout:** 30 seconds per request"},"1075":{"id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server-23","page_id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server#api-compatibility","content":"Code written for the local library works unchanged with the client:"},"1076":{"id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server-24","page_id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server#when-to-use-which","content":"Use case"},"1077":{"id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server-25","page_id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server#when-to-use-which","content":"Package"},"1078":{"id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server-26","page_id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server#when-to-use-which","content":"Install path"},"1079":{"id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server-27","page_id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server#when-to-use-which","content":"Development, testing, research"},"1080":{"id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server-28","page_id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server#when-to-use-which","content":"`flopscope` (local library)"},"1081":{"id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server-29","page_id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server#when-to-use-which","content":"`uv add git+...` or `uv sync` from repo"},"1082":{"id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server-30","page_id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server#when-to-use-which","content":"Competition evaluation, sandboxed environments"},"1083":{"id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server-31","page_id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server#when-to-use-which","content":"`flopscope-client` + `flopscope-server`"},"1084":{"id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server-32","page_id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server#when-to-use-which","content":"Docker containers"},"1085":{"id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server-33","page_id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server#three-packages-in-this-repo","content":"Package"},"1086":{"id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server-34","page_id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server#three-packages-in-this-repo","content":"Location"},"1087":{"id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server-35","page_id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server#three-packages-in-this-repo","content":"Description"},"1088":{"id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server-36","page_id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server#three-packages-in-this-repo","content":"`flopscope`"},"1089":{"id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server-37","page_id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server#three-packages-in-this-repo","content":"`src/flopscope/`"},"1090":{"id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server-38","page_id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server#three-packages-in-this-repo","content":"Local library — full NumPy backend, direct execution"},"1091":{"id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server-39","page_id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server#three-packages-in-this-repo","content":"`flopscope-client`"},"1092":{"id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server-40","page_id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server#three-packages-in-this-repo","content":"`flopscope-client/`"},"1093":{"id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server-41","page_id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server#three-packages-in-this-repo","content":"Client proxy — no NumPy dependency, forwards ops to server"},"1094":{"id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server-42","page_id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server#three-packages-in-this-repo","content":"`flopscope-server`"},"1095":{"id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server-43","page_id":"/docs/infrastructure/client-server","tags":[],"t