odel","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","content":"**You will learn:**"},"1162":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-22","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","content":"How Flopscope computes FLOP costs analytically from tensor shapes"},"1163":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-23","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","content":"How cost formulas work for each operation category (einsum, linalg, FFT, etc.)"},"1164":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-24","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","content":"How symmetry savings and per-operation weights modify costs"},"1165":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-25","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","content":"How the FLOP multiplier and namespaces interact with the cost model"},"1166":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-26","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#convention-fma--1-operation","content":"This codebase counts a fused multiply-add (a \\* b + c) as a **single operation**.\nHardware FMA units execute this in one instruction; the common textbook\nconvention of counting it as 2 (one multiply + one add) is **not** used here.\nAll cost formulae reflect this: a matrix multiply of dimensions\n(m, k) x (k, n) costs m*k*n operations, not 2*m*k\\*n."},"1167":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-27","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#why-flops-instead-of-wall-clock-time","content":"**Deterministic:** The same